<!-- What Is Fertigation -->
<section class="section">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="two-col-layout" style="align-items:center;">
            <div>
                <span class="section-eyebrow">The Concept</span>
                <h2>Irrigation and Fertilization — As One</h2>
                <p>Fertigation is the practice of injecting fertilizers, acids, and other soluble products directly into your irrigation water. Because drip systems deliver water to the root zone, fertigation products follow the same path — going exactly where plants can absorb them.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px;">The result is dramatically better nutrient use efficiency: crops take up more of what they're given, less leaches into groundwater, and you spend less per acre on inputs.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="benefit-stat-card" style="align-self:start;">
                <div class="big-stat"><span class="big-number">40%</span><span class="big-label">Typical fertilizer cost reduction</span></div>
                <div class="big-stat"><span class="big-number">90%+</span><span class="big-label">Nutrient uptake efficiency via fertigation</span></div>
                <div class="big-stat"><span class="big-number">0</span><span class="big-label">Surface broadcast labor required</span></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- Why It Works -->
<section class="section" style="background:var(--blue-pale);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">The Science</span>
            <h2>Why Root-Zone Nutrition Outperforms Broadcast</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid" style="margin-top:40px;">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🎯</div>
                <h3>Right Place</h3>
                <p>Broadcast fertilizer relies on rainfall or flood irrigation to move nutrients down to roots — often unevenly. Fertigation delivers nutrients directly into the active root zone where uptake happens immediately.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">📅</div>
                <h3>Right Time</h3>
                <p>Crops don't need all their nitrogen in one shot at planting. Fertigation enables split applications matched to actual crop demand at each growth stage — dramatically improving use efficiency.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">⚖️</div>
                <h3>Right Rate</h3>
                <p>Injection pumps can be programmed to apply precise amounts per zone and per irrigation event — eliminating the over-application that comes from estimating broadcast rates on variable soils.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- What You Can Inject -->
<section class="section">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Inputs</span>
            <h2>What Can Be Applied Through Fertigation</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="two-col-layout" style="margin-top:40px; gap:24px;">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🧪</div>
                <h3>Soluble Fertilizers</h3>
                <p>N, P, K, and micro-nutrient solutions in liquid or dissolved form. Calcium nitrate, potassium nitrate, mono-ammonium phosphate, and compound NPK blends are commonly fertigated.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🫙</div>
                <h3>Acids for pH Management</h3>
                <p>Phosphoric or sulfuric acid injection lowers irrigation water pH — critical in high-bicarbonate water areas to prevent calcium/magnesium precipitation in emitters.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌿</div>
                <h3>Bio-Stimulants</h3>
                <p>Humic acids, fulvic acids, seaweed extracts, and beneficial microbe solutions can be fertigated — improving soil biology and plant stress response without additional field passes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🛡️</div>
                <h3>Chlorination</h3>
                <p>Periodic chlorine injection prevents biological clogging in the system from algae and bacterial biofilm growth — particularly important for surface water and recycled water sources.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

